Q.1 Introduction to Compliance within Fintech [15M]
Definition:
•	Compliance in fintech ensures that digital financial services operate according to regulatory standards, security requirements, and best practices to protect customer data and maintain trust.
________________________________________
(a) Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) [7–8M]
•	Definition: A global standard that protects cardholder data during payment processing.
•	Key Requirements:
1.	Build and maintain a secure network (firewalls, network segmentation).
2.	Protect cardholder data with encryption in storage and transit.
3.	Implement strong access control measures (unique IDs, role-based access).
4.	Regularly monitor and test networks for vulnerabilities.
5.	Maintain an information security policy for employees.
•	Importance in Fintech:
•	Prevents fraud and data breaches.
•	Ensures secure card transactions.
•	Maintains customer trust.
________________________________________
(b) RBI PSS (Reserve Bank of India – Payment and Settlement Systems) [7–8M]
•	Definition: Framework by the Reserve Bank of India regulating all payment and settlement systems in India.
•	Key Components:
1.	RTGS (Real-Time Gross Settlement): Instant settlement of high-value interbank transactions.
2.	NEFT (National Electronic Funds Transfer): Batch-based retail payments.
3.	UPI (Unified Payments Interface): Instant mobile payments system.
4.	Clearing Systems: Netting and reconciliation between banks.
•	Compliance Requirements:
•	Banks must follow RBI operational standards, secure transactions, maintain audit logs, and monitor fraud.
•	Importance in Fintech:
•	Ensures secure, efficient, and regulated payment services in India.
