Q.1 Mobile Banking vs Internet Banking & UPI Technology [15M]
(a) Which is more secure: Mobile Banking or Internet Banking? [5M]
1.	Mobile Banking Security:
•	Apps use multi-factor authentication (MFA), device fingerprinting, and app sandboxing.
•	Sensitive data is encrypted at rest and in transit.
•	Less exposed to phishing via email compared to web-based internet banking.
2.	Internet Banking Security:
•	Relies on web browsers, which can be vulnerable to malware, phishing, and session hijacking.
•	Security depends on SSL/TLS encryption, strong passwords, and anti-virus software.
Conclusion:
•	Mobile banking is generally considered more secure than internet banking due to app-level security controls and reduced exposure to web-based attacks.
________________________________________
(b) How Mobile Banking Works Without Internet [5M]
•	USSD (Unstructured Supplementary Service Data):
•	Uses cellular network to send commands and receive responses.
•	Example: Dial *99# for UPI-based banking.
•	SMS Banking:
•	Transaction requests sent via encrypted SMS to bank servers.
•	Limitations:
•	Limited transaction types (balance enquiry, fund transfer, mini-statement).
•	Requires mobile network coverage but not internet connectivity.
________________________________________
(c) Which technology is used in UPI?  [5M]
1.	IMPS (Immediate Payment Service): Enables instant fund transfers 24×7.
2.	Mobile Application Layer: Interfaces like BHIM, Google Pay, or PhonePe.
3.	UPI API Gateway: Connects banks and third-party apps.
4.	Two-Factor Authentication: Ensures secure transactions using PIN and device verification.
5.	End-to-End Encryption: Secures payment instructions between sender and recipient.
